    <section class="page-header">
      <h1 class="project-name">Particle/Arduino RC Car</h1>
      <h2 class="project-tagline">code and step-by-step docs for controlling an RC car via Particle and Arduino boards</h2>
      <a href="https://github.com/jasonpvp/particle-arduino-car" class="btn">View on GitHub</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/jasonpvp/particle-arduino-car/zipball/master" class="btn">Download .zip</a>
      <a href="https://github.com/jasonpvp/particle-arduino-car/tarball/master" class="btn">Download .tar.gz</a>
    </section>

    <section class="main-content">
      <h2>
<h4>
<a id="1-connect-the-rc-car-to-the-arduino" class="anchor" href="#1-connect-the-rc-car-to-the-arduino" aria-hidden="true"><span class="octicon octicon-link"></span></a>1: Connect the RC car to the Arduino</h4>

<ul>
<li>
<p>Components required</p>
<h6>Note: Links below are not where I purchased my components - just random links for reference. When noted the items are the actual ones I used</h6>

<ul>
<li>1 RC car (I got the  <a target="_blank" href="http://www.minimodelshop.co.uk/rc-model/rock-crawler-radio-controlled-car-maisto-81152bk">Maisto Rock Crawler</a> for $25)</li>
<li>1 <a target="_blank" href="https://www.arduino.cc/en/Guide/HomePage">Arduino</a> (I have an <a href="https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/arduinoBoardUno">Uno</a> R2)</li>
<li>1 <a target="_blank" href="https://www.arduino.cc/en/Main/ArduinoMotorShieldR3">Arduino motor shield</a> (I used this, but there were some catches)</li>
<li>12 <a target="_blank" href="http://www.makershed.com/products/deluxe-breadboard-jumper-wires?gclid=CKbN6cqI7scCFQiVfgodnogJ-w">jumper wires</a></li>
<li><a target="_blank" href="https://www.sparkfun.com/products/retired/11210">soldering equipment</a></li>
<li><a target="_blank" href="http://www.adafruit.com/products/65?gclid=CJmIhv-O7scCFcNgfgodV0oAwQ">1 breadboard</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>
<p>Solder jumper wires to your RC car</p>

<p>I got lucky in finding <a href="http://www.rcgroups.com/forums/showthread.php?t=1651494">instructions</a> to connect to the exact RC car I had purchased, but a little googling turned up a number of <a target="_blank" href="http://www.intorobotics.com/build-robot-without-arduino-shield-r3-dc-stepper-motors-controlled/">different examples</a>.  Basically you need to solder jumper wires to the forward, backward, left and right signal pins on the car's main IC chip and two more to the positive battery and ground terminals.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Test your soldering</p>

<ul>
<li>If the car still drives with the RC controller, you've probably succeeded in not breaking it!</li>
<li>You can test your solders by connecting each of the IC wires to the car's power in turn. If the car's main power is more than a few volts you should use a resistor in the connection to protect the IC.  If anything doesn't work check your solders. This is also a good time to label the wires like so:
  <table>
    <tr><td><b>Label</b></td><td><b>Function</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Vcc</td><td>Positive power terminal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Gnd</td><td>Ground terminal</td></tr>
    <tr><td>F</td><td>Forward signal pin</td></tr>
    <tr><td>B</td><td>Reverse signal pin</td></tr>
    <tr><td>L</td><td>Left signal pin</td></tr>
    <tr><td>R</td><td>Right signal pin</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p></p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p><a href="https://github.com/jasonpvp/particle-arduino-car/blob/master/src/step_1_arduino_to_car/drive_car_test_1.ino">Program the Arduino to drive your car</a></p></li>
<li>
<p>Connect the Arduino to your car</p>

<ul>
<li>Connect the car's new jumper wires to your Arduino like so:
  <table>
    <tr><td><b>Car</b></td><td><b>Motor shield</b></td></tr>
    <tr><td>Vcc</td><td>Vin</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Gnd</td><td>Gnd</td></tr>
    <tr><td>F</td><td>A+</td></tr>
    <tr><td>B</td><td>A-</td></tr>
    <tr><td>L</td><td>B+</td></tr>
    <tr><td>R</td><td>B-</td></tr>
  </table>
  <p></p>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><p>Test it out!
With the above program on your Arduino and the board wired to the car, the drive and steering motors should ramp up from 0 to 100% every few seconds.</p></li>
</ul>

